	<h2>The Reality of Summer Sublets</h2>
	<p>Securing short-term housing in New York City is notoriously difficult. Unlike a standard 12-month lease, landlords rarely sign direct two-month contracts. This leaves interns battling for sublets from college students leaving the city or navigating corporate housing.</p>
	
	<h3>Sourcing a Sublet</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>University Facebook Groups:</strong> Columbia and NYU students regularly sublet their off-campus apartments during the summer. Monitor groups like "NYU Housing, Sublets & Roommates" daily starting in March.</li>
		<li><strong>Corporate Housing:</strong> If your company offers a stipend, evaluate dedicated intern housing like Educational Housing Services (EHS) or New York University's summer dorm program. These are heavily vetted and avoid the risk of scams.</li>
		<li><strong>Lease Takeovers:</strong> Be prepared to move fast. Good sublets in the East Village or West Village disappear within hours of posting.</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Avoiding Scams</h3>
	<p>Never wire money or send a Venmo deposit before viewing an apartment either in person or via a live FaceTime tour. If a price seems abnormally low for Downtown Manhattan (e.g., $1,200 for a private 1-bedroom), it is definitively a scam.</p>
</InternWiki>
